    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's focus on the scientific details of mitosis:\n\n1. Prophase: Chromosomes condense and become visible. The nuclear envelope breaks down, and the mitotic spindle begins to form from the centrosomes, which move to opposite poles of the cell.\n\n2. Metaphase: Chromosomes align at the metaphase plate, an imaginary line equidistant from the two spindle poles. The spindle fibers attach to the centromeres of the chromosomes.\n\n3. Anaphase: Sister chromatids are pulled apart by the spindle fibers towards opposite poles of the cell. This separation ensures that each new cell will receive an identical set of chromosomes.\n\n4. Telophase: Chromosomes arrive at the poles and begin to de-condense. The nuclear envelope re-forms around each set of chromosomes, resulting in two separate nuclei within the cell.\n\n5. Cytokinesis: The cytoplasm divides, resulting in two genetically identical daughter cells, each with a complete set of chromosomes.\n\nI hope this helps with your exam preparation. Let me know if you need more details on any specific stage.",
